“The sea belongs to us”: a Bolivia without a coastline has the hope that the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
Navy marines guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
Flags are flying at half-mast in public buildings.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right."
It is a duty to recover it."
In all of Bolivia, a land without a sea, people still remember vividly the lost coast before Chile in a bloody conflict for the resources that took place in the 19th century, as well as the longing to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
These hopes may be the greatest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on October 1st, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and calmness and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the failure of the International Court of Justice on large screens spread throughout the country, hoping that the International Court of Justice in The Hague will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent negotiations, Chile has the obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is locked in a controversial battle for reelection next year, also has a lot to say about the resolution.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the tribunal will rule in Bolivia's favor and that the situation would change little if it did.
The United Nations agency based in the Netherlands does not have the power to adjudicate territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any possible negotiations.
The fact that the resolution of the International Court of Justice came only six months after the final arguments indicates that the case "wasn't complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
Far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have actually hindered it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” said Zárate.
In addition, he suggested that the bellicose rhetoric of Morales has eroded any residual good will in Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to have conversations after this.
The two countries do not exchange ambassadors since 1962.
Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, the Bolivian representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will offer Chile "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of "putting an end to 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits", said.
In addition, Calzadilla denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, was using the maritime issue as a political tool.
“Bolivia will never renounce its right to have access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The resolution is an opportunity to see what we need to leave behind.”
