John Edward: linguistic skills are fundamental for citizens of the world
Scotland's independent schools have a long history of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes in sport, the arts, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students in all of Scotland, these independent schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for its acronym in English), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
The purpose of independent schools is to prepare their students for further education, for the career they choose, and for the place they will occupy in the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message goes to his head. If you talk to him in his language, the message goes to his heart."
If you talk to them in their own language, it reaches their heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries, you can't rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that the languages are at the top of the classification tables, with the pass rates being the highest in independent schools.
In total, 68 % of the students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 % of the students got an A in Mandarin, while 72 % of the students who studied German, 69 % of the students who studied French, and 63 % of the students who studied Spanish also got an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support the teaching of foreign languages because they see them as a fundamental skill that children and young people will definitely need in the future without a doubt.
Today, it is considered that languages are at the same level as the CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the Commission for Employment and Skills in the United Kingdom revealed that, of the reasons given by employers on the difficulties they faced in filling jobs, 17 % were attributed to the lack of linguistic skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming more and more essential for preparing young people for their future careers.
The possible employment opportunities that require language skills are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last their whole life.
The fact of being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to get ahead of the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 % of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only foreign language spoken by a two-digit percentage, the 15 %, was French.
For this reason, investing in the teaching of languages now is important for children of today.
If children know more than one language, especially those of developing economies, they will be better equipped to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach a different language.
Some centres will focus on the classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools they can choose between several languages taught by specialist teachers in this field.
Scotland's independent schools devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
It is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have an important role to play in the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, the modern languages must be considered "competencies for international communication."
The independent schools in Scotland will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
You've got to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
