North Korea says that "there is no possibility" of disarming first unilaterally if they do not have confidence.
On Saturday, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened their mistrust of the United States and that there was no possibility that they would renounce their nuclear armament unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared before the General Assembly of the international organization that North Korea had adopted "important measures of goodwill" over the course of the past year, such as ceasing nuclear tests and missile launches, dismantling nuclear test sites, and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
However, we did not receive a similar response from the United States.
"If we don't have confidence in the United States, we can't have confidence in our national security, and, in those circumstances, there is no chance that we will disarm unilaterally."
Although Ri repeated the well-known complaints of North Korea about the resistance of Washington to a "phased" denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes steps, his statement is important, since he did not reject a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri made reference to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between a U.S. president in office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, 2018, when Kim pledged to work toward denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the Korean War of 1950-53, but the U.S. has said that Pyongyang must renounce its nuclear weapons first.
In addition, Washington has resisted calls to soften the international sanctions on North Korea.
"The U.S. has insisted on nuclear disarmament first and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its goal coercively, even objecting to a declaration of termination of the war," Ri said.
The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a fantasy of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of the sanctions deepens our mistrust.
Ri did not mention any plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced with great fanfare by the U.S. president at the U.N. General Assembly a few weeks ago.
Instead of that, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, the leader of South Korea, in the last five months, and added: "If South Korea had been the interested party in the denuclearization of the peninsula instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the peninsula would not be in such a stalemate."
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's speech, when he said to the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct the missiles of North Korea towards US soil after the "malignant president" Trump, on a suicidal mission, called Kim "rocket man".
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving towards disarmament, but said that there was still much to do and that sanctions would have to be applied until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump stated that there was no deadline for this: "We can take two years, three years, or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the United Nations Security Council should reward North Korea for its advances.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday, "The sanctions imposed by the Security Council must continue energetically and in full compliance until we realize a complete, verifiable and irreversible denuclearization."
The Security Council has imposed sanctions unanimously on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut off funding for the country's ballistic missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the United Nations General Assembly and then commented that he would return to Pyongyang in a month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but, a few hours later, North Korea announced that its "demands were those of a gangster."
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea agreed to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the U.S. took “corresponding measures.”
He said that Kim had told him that the "measures" he was looking for were the guarantees of security that Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough sleep.
Thanks to a new course that is being taught this year at Harvard University, all the students are sleeping more in an attempt to fight against the growing culture of studying all night drinking coffee.
A professor discovered that the students of the number one university in the world do not have any idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at the Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how lack of sleep affects learning.
At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked why she was just finding out about this now, at the end of her last year.
He said that no one had ever spoken to him before about the importance of sleep, which surprised me.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at the Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were barely sleeping during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, running shoes, and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
After that, an icon of the campus with interactive icons animates the participants to think about their daily routines.
We know that this is not going to change the behavior of the students immediately.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco.
He said that the culture of pride for "staying up all night" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure students are under meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and a good night's sleep should be "the secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since lack of sleep makes the brain generate a feeling of hunger, so that they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying biochemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after having attended one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the whole campus.
