Almanac: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now, a page from the Almanac section of the “Sunday Morning”: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago, and COUNTING... was born in Germany the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that culminated with the device known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter, which since then has become a pillar of science, also became a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 movie "The Bells of Coronado", with the actors Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in the apparently incompatible roles of scientists cowboys:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, it's used to locate radioactive minerals, like uranium."
When you put on the earphones, you can hear the effect of the radioactivity emitted by the minerals.
Evans: "It's like a radio!"
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, when he was about to turn 63.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
A new vaccine against cancer may teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells.
A new vaccine against cancer may teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells and kill them.
As part of the treatment, the vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize cancerous cells.
The method requires the extraction of immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory.
Thus, they can "see" a common protein in many cancers and re-inject them.
A clinical trial of the vaccine is generating promising results in patients with different cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method requires the extraction of immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2, and, subsequently, reinjecting the cells.
Jay Berzofsky, a professor at the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, commented: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "promotes the growth of different types of cancer", such as breast, ovary, lung or colorectal cancer, explained the professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and "teaching" them to attack cancerous cells has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
