HIV/AIDS: China reports of a 14 % increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14 % in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
In the country, there are more than 820,000 people affected, according to the health authorities.
Only in the second quarter of 2018, some 40,000 new cases were reported.
The majority of these were infected through sexual contact, which is a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread quickly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who contract HIV in this way has been reduced in its entirety, according to Chinese health authorities at a conference held in the province of Yunnan.
Every year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100 000 people.
The transmission of HIV through sexual intercourse is a serious problem in the LGTB community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGTB community still suffers from a lot of discrimination.
Due to the conservative nature of the country, studies have calculated that between 70 % and 90 % of men who have sexual relations with other men will end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of the diseases are due to not using adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the government of China has promised universal access to anti-retroviral drugs as part of an effort to confront the problem.
Representative Maxine Waters denies that a member of her staff leaked data to Republican senators and states that it is "dangerous lies" and "conspiracy theories."
Representative Maxine Waters criticized Saturday the allegations that a member of her staff had published the personal data of three U.S. Republican senators on the Wikipedia pages of legislators.
