Review of Johnny English: Again in Action. Rowan Atkinson's parody of the spy fails to deliver
Now it has become a tradition to look for guffaws at the Brexit in any new movie with a British focus. It seems that this is what you should do with this new installment of the parodic action and comedy Johnny English, which started in 2003 with Johnny English and returned to life in 2011 with Johnny English Returns.
Will this ironic self-satire be the new opportunity for exporting the nation's insanity?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English, with his bulging eyes and expressionless face, has renewed his license for the second time. Just his name already gives away that, more than anything else, it is a comedy created for non-English speaking territories.
Of course, it's the ridiculous secret agent who, despite his strange pretensions of squandering glamour, has a bit of Clouseau, a touch of Mr. Bean and a pinch of that type who touched a single note in the theme of Chariots of Fire that touched a single note in the opening ceremony of the London Olympics.
In addition, it was based on the mysterious man traveler and international represented years ago by Atkinson in the forgotten television ads of Barclaycard, sowing chaos behind him.
In this last episode, there are a couple of good moments.
I loved seeing Johnny English approaching a helicopter dressed as a medieval knight while the helicopter's rotors hit his helmet.
Atkinson's gift for physical comedy jumps off the screen, but the humor is a bit short and is oddly superfluous, especially now that franchises like James Bond and Mission: Impossible are adding comic ingredients without problems.
The humor seems to be more directed to children than to adults, and for me, the absurd adventures of Johnny English are not as clever and accurate as the silent jokes of Atkinson in the role of Mr. Bean.
Now, the oft-repeated argument is that Britain is in deep trouble.
A hacker has infiltrated the super-secret network of spies of Great Britain, revealing the identities of all its active agents to the consternation of the agent in service, a lamentably small role for Kevin Eldon.
It's the straw that breaks the camel's back for the prime minister, a pompous and cornered character who is watching her popularity sink: Emma Thompson gives the best of herself in this character that is almost like Theresa May, but the script doesn't leave much room to work.
His intelligence advisors inform him that, as all active spies are in danger, he will have to rely on one who is retired.
That has to be the clumsy Johnny English, who now teaches at a posh private school, although he also teaches extra-curricular classes on how to be a secret agent: there are some good jokes, since it is a spy academy similar to the one in School of Rock.
English is transferred to Whitehall for an urgent meeting and meets up with his old friend Bough, played again by Ben Miller.
Now, Bough is a married man with a submariner captain, a role that he doesn't take advantage of enough with Vicki Pepperdine.
So, the Batman and Robin that do things terribly wrong in the Secret Service of Her Majesty return to action, with the beautiful woman fatal Ophelia Bulletova, represented by Olga Kurylenko.
Meanwhile, the Prime Minister is falling into the dangerous claws of a charismatic multi-millionaire from the world of technology who claims he can solve the IT problems of Britain: the sinister Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their odyssey of absurd situations: they disguise themselves as waiters, set fire to a fancy French restaurant, cause chaos by hiding on the luxurious yacht of Volta; in addition, English becomes pure anarchy when he tries to use a virtual reality helmet to familiarize himself with the interior of Volta's house.
Undoubtedly, they put a lot of effort into that last sequence, but, however funny and noisy it may be, the whole thing still has a somewhat childish feel to it.
A fairly regular product.
Just like with the other Johnny English movies, I couldn't help but wonder if the British film industry couldn't give Rowan Atkinson a role that would truly do justice to his talent.
