What is the "Global Citizen Festival"? Has it been able to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music festival that brings together a star-studded lineup in support of an equally star-studded mission: ending poverty in the world.
This year, in its seventh edition, the Global Citizen Festival will see how tens of thousands of people will move to Central Park's Great Lawn to enjoy performances by Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness about the real objective of the event: to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international awareness group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people who actively fight against it.
If you would like to receive a free entry to the event (unless you can afford a VIP ticket), attendees to the concerts have had to complete a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending emails to a world leader, making a phone call or any other thing that serves to raise awareness about their goal to end poverty.
However, what has the Global Citizen achieved after 12 years of reaching its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding with a free concert a genuine way of persuading people to take action or is it just a form of "clicktivism", which refers to the position we adopt when we think we are doing something really useful by signing a petition online or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has claimed to have registered more than 19 million "actions" by its supporters in favor of a large number of different objectives.
Thanks to these actions, they claim to have achieved commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people in 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements that emerged from their actions, of which, at least 10 000 million $ have already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that the guaranteed funds have had a direct impact on almost 649 million people around the world.
Among the most important commitments is "The Power of Nutrition," an association of investors and implementers based in the United Kingdom with the common goal of "helping children grow and develop to their full potential." With this in mind, they have pledged to provide $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizen collaborators.
Thanks to the support of the government of the United Kingdom, the donors, the national governments and collaborators of Global Citizens like you, we can mark a small milestone in the history of social injustice of malnutrition," said Tracey Ullman, ambassador of "The Power of Nutrition", to the crowd during a concert in April 2018 in London.
The group also stated that, after having carried out more than 5,000 actions to improve nutrition in the United Kingdom for mothers and children, the government announced the funding of a project, Power of Nutrition, with which 5 million women and children will benefit from nutrition-related interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on their website about what we think can be done to alleviate extreme poverty,
A Global Citizen collaborator responded: "It will be a long and difficult road and, in many cases, we will stumble and fall."
But, as they have already succeeded in the movements for human rights and against apartheid, we will achieve our goals, because we are stronger together.
Janet Jackson, The Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are some of the performances we will have at the New York event this year, which will be presented by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
The U.S. could use the Navy to carry out the blockade of Russian energy exports - Department of the Interior
In case necessary, Washington could resort to its Navy to prevent the Russian energy from shaking the markets, including the Middle East, revealed the Secretary of the Interior of the United States, Ryan Zinke, according to what is published in the Washington Examiner.
Zinke claimed that Russia's alliance with Syria, in particular where it operates on behalf of the legitimate government, is no more than a pretext for expansion into new markets.
I am convinced that they are in the Middle East to negotiate with energy, as they do in Eastern Europe, becoming the main supplier of energy to Europe.
In addition, according to official information, there are ways and methods of dealing with this issue.
"The United States, with its Navy, has the capacity to guarantee that the maritime routes remain open and, if necessary, could even block them to ensure that the energy does not end up in the market," he said.
Zinke spoke to the people who attended an event organized by the Consumer Energy Alliance, a non-profit group that describes itself as the "voice of the consumer energy industry" in the United States.
In it, he compared the approaches that Washington has taken in its negotiations with Russia and Iran, and warned that they are, in fact, the same.
"The alternative economic model in Iran and Russia consists, basically, of exploiting and replacing fossil fuels," he warned at the same time that he indicated that Russia only knows how to do one thing, which is to base its economy on fossil fuels.
These statements are made when the Trump administration has been trying to promote the exportation of liquefied natural gas to Europe and replace Russia, which is the cheapest option for European consumers.
For this purpose, members of the Trump administration, including Donald Trump himself, are trying to persuade Germany to abandon the "inappropriate" Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project, which, according to Trump, will turn Berlin into a hostage of Moscow.
Moscow has insisted at all times that the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project, which has a value of $11 billion and is intended to double the current capacity of the gas pipeline to $22 billion cubic meters, is a purely economic project.
The Kremlin defends that the fervent opposition of Washington to the project responds only to economic motives and is another example of unfair competition.
"I think we all share the idea that energy cannot be converted into a tool of pressure and that consumers should be able to choose their suppliers," said the Minister of Energy of Russia, Aleksandr Novak, after a meeting with Rick Perry, the Secretary of Energy of the United States, in Moscow in September 2017.
The U.S. position has found itself, however, with the rejection of Germany, which has reaffirmed its commitment to the project.
The organization that leads the industry in Germany, the Federation of German Industries (BDI), has asked the U.S. not to intervene in the energy policy of the EU nor in the bilateral agreements between Berlin and Moscow.
“It’s a big problem when a third state interferes in our energy supply,” said Dieter Kempf, director of the Federation of German Industries (BDI), after a meeting that took place recently between the German Chancellor, Angela Merkel, and the Russian President, Vladimir Putin.
