18 states, D.C. support the challenge to achieve a new asylum policy
18 states and the District of Columbia have filed a lawsuit against the Trump administration's new policy that denies asylum to victims of domestic violence or gang violence.
Representatives from the 18 states and the District of Columbia presented a "friendly" letter on Friday in Washington to show their support for an asylum seeker who is currently facing the current directive, according to NBC News.
The name of the plaintiff in the case "Grace v. Sessions" presented in August by the ACLU (American Civil Liberties Union) in opposition to the federal policy has not been revealed.
She said that her partner "and his children, who are members of a violent gang," abused her, but the U.S. officials denied her request for asylum on July 20.
She was arrested in Texas.
Lawyers who represent these states that defend Grace described El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala, which generate a large number of asylum requests to the U.S., as nations that face generalized problems related to domestic violence and gang violence.
The new asylum policy of the United States revoked a decision of 2014 taken by the Board of Immigration Appeals (BIA, for its acronym in English) by which undocumented immigrants who flee domestic violence could apply for asylum in this country.
The Attorney General of the District of Columbia, Karl Racine, made some statements on Friday in which he said that the new policy "ignores decades of international, federal and state law."
According to federal law, all asylum requests must be denied on the basis of the facts and circumstances of the particular claim and, instead, this exception violates that principle.
In addition, the lawyers pointed out in the letter that the policy that denies entry to immigrants hurts the economy of the U.S. by asserting that they tend to become entrepreneurs more often and "represent a necessary workforce."
