The U.S. ambassador to China accuses China of "bullying" with "propaganda announcements"
One week after a Chinese official newspaper published a four-page advertisement in a U.S. newspaper touting the mutual benefits of trade between the U.S. and China, the U.S. ambassador to China accused Beijing of using the U.S. press to spread its propaganda.
On Wednesday, the President of the United States, Donald Trump, made reference to the supplement of the China Daily in the Des Moines Register, the most sold newspaper in Iowa, after accusing China of trying to interfere in the elections to the Congress of the United States on November 6, something that China denies in a very clear way.
Trump's accusation that Beijing was trying to influence U.S. elections marked a new phase in a growing U.S. campaign to pressure China.
While it is common for foreign governments to publish advertisements to promote their commercial activities, Beijing and Washington are currently locked in a growing trade war that has led both sides to increase tariff levels on imports from each other.
The compensatory tariffs that China applied at the beginning of the trade war were designed to fall on exporters in states like Iowa, which supported the Republican Party of Trump, according to Chinese and American experts.
Terry Branstad, the U.S. ambassador to China and the former governor of Iowa, who is one of the main exporters of agricultural products to China, said that Beijing had harmed American workers, farmers and business people.
As Branstad wrote in an op-ed in the Des Moines Register on Sunday, China is "intensifying that pressure even more by running ads in our free press."
To try to spread its propaganda, the Chinese government is taking advantage of the cherished American tradition of freedom of expression and free press by trying to publish an ad in the Des Moines Register.
In contrast, in the newsstand on the street where we are here in Beijing, there are only a few voices of dissent and no real reflection of the diverse opinions that the people of China can have on the worrying trajectory that their economy is taking, since the media are controlled by the firm pressure of the Communist Party of China.
He added that "one of the most relevant newspapers in China refused to publish" his article, although he did not specify which newspaper.
Analysts point out that the Republicans are distancing themselves from women before the midterm elections with the Kavanaugh debacle.
As many Republicans of note are closing ranks in favor of Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh in the face of various sexual assault allegations, analysts have warned that this could lead to a backlash, especially among women, in the upcoming mid-term elections.
The emotions surrounding this fact have been very intense, and many Republicans have stated that they want to move forward with the vote.
Grant Reeher, a professor of political science at the Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs at Syracuse University, told The Hill in an article that was published on Saturday.
Reeher doubts that Senator Jeff Flake's (R-Arizona) last attempt to position himself in favor of the FBI's investigation will be enough to calm the disgruntled voters on this issue.
“Women are not going to forget what happened yesterday; they’re not going to forget tomorrow, or in November,” said Karine Jean-Pierre, a senior adviser and spokesperson for the progressive group MoveOn, according to the Washington Post.
On Friday morning, the protesters who gathered at the doors of the Senate were chanting "November is coming!" (November is coming soon!) at the moment when the Republicans who controlled the Judicial Committee decided to go ahead with the nomination of Kavanaugh, despite the testimony of Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, as reported by the Mic.
Stu Rothenberg, a non-partisan political analyst, said, "The enthusiasm and motivation of the Democrats is way out of the ballpark."
People say that the impact is already very relevant and, in fact, that is so.
But it could be even greater, especially among the indecisive voters from the outskirts of the city and the younger voters between the ages of 18 and 29, who don't usually vote even though they don't like the president."
Even before Ford's public testimony in which she detailed in great detail her allegations of sexual assault against the Supreme Court nominee, analysts indicated that there could be a backslide if the Republicans continued ahead with the confirmation.
“This has turned into a big mess for the Republican Party,” said Michael Steele, the former chairman of the Republican National Committee, as reported by NBC News earlier this week.
"It's not just about the vote of the committee or the final vote, or even if they sit on the bench with Kavanaugh; it's also about how the Republicans have handled all of this and how they've treated her," said Guy Cecil, director of Priorities USA (a group that helps elect Democrats).
However, the Americans seem to be divided; they don't know who to believe after the testimonies of Ford and Kavanaugh, although there are a few more who are on Kavanaugh's side.
In a new YouGov poll, it is indicated that 41% of the respondents believe Ford's testimony definitively or probably, while 35% believe Kavanaugh's testimony definitively or probably.
In addition, 38 % said they thought Kavanaugh lied during his testimony, while 30 % said the same of Ford.
After Flake's push, the FBI is currently investigating Ford's statements as well as at least those of another accuser, Deborah Ramirez, as reported by The Guardian.
Ford testified under oath before the Senate Judiciary Committee last week and indicated that Kavanaugh sexually assaulted her while she was drunk at the age of 17.
On the other hand, Ramirez claimed that the candidate for the Supreme Court showed his genitals to him at a party when he was studying at Yale in the 1980s.
The inventor of the World Wide Web is planning to start a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is putting together a new company that is trying to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the last project of the legend of technology. A company that is based on the open source code platform Solid of Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention that lies behind Inrupt is "to dominate the world."
“It has to be now,” he said about the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses the technology of Solid to allow users to create their own "personal data storage space" or a POD.
It can contain lists, lists of pending tasks, the calendar, the music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It's like if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify were all available in the same browser at the same time.
One thing that is exclusive to online personal data storage is that the user is the one who decides completely who can access what type of information.
The company calls it "personal data training through data."
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate resources, processes and the skills necessary for Solid to reach the whole world.
For the moment, the company is formed by Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the developers included in the staff that were hired to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week, developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps with the tools that are available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking with "Facebook and Google about whether they are going to introduce or not a radical change where all their business models are going to be completely modified from one day to the other."
"We're not going to ask permission."
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote about Inrupt that "its mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new web created in Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In the last few months, Berners-Lee has had a very influential role in the debate over the neutrality of the Internet.
Even though Berners-Lee is launching Inrupt, he will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
Berners-Lee said he was "incredibly optimistic" about the next era of the web.
Bernard Vann: the clergyman who won a Victoria Cross in the First World War
The only clergyman of the Church of England who won a Victoria Cross during the First World War has been honoured in his home town 100 years after his death.
Lt. Col. Rev. Bernard Vann received this decoration on September 29, 1918 in the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, a sniper killed him four days later and he never knew that he had been awarded the highest honor in the British military.
On Saturday, the couple's two grandchildren discovered a commemorative stone in a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of them, Michael Vann, said that it was "of a special symbolism" that the stone was discovered exactly 100 years after the battle that earned his grandfather the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a dense fog and under the intense fire of machine guns and cannons."
Then he ran to the line of fire and, with the "greatest bravery", he advanced the line before reaching a cannon with one hand and knocking out three of the detachment.
Lt. Col. Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just one month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "so great that I will never be able to reach his level, but they were very instructive."
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade, which was accompanied by the participation of the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that "it was a privilege for him to be able to take part in the parade" and added that "the true value of a genuine hero becomes apparent when he is shown such a strong show of support."
