Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says that he grew up feeling inferior because of his sexuality, but this was what motivated him to become a champion.
At 24 years old, she told us that she didn't realize it until she got to high school that "not everyone was like me."
In the first episode of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, presented by Lauren Laverne, she said her intention in talking about gay rights was to "transmit hope" to other people.
He also told us that becoming a father made him start to put less importance on winning at the Olympics.
The regular presenter of this mythical program, Kirsty Young, is going to be absent for a few months due to illness.
In the first episode of Laverne, Daley, who showed himself as an outcast, commented that he felt "inferior" to the rest during his childhood, because "it was not socially acceptable to like boys and girls."
She said: "Until today, the feeling of inferiority and being different has been what has really given me the power and strength to succeed."
He wanted to show that he was "something," he said, so he didn't disappoint when he finally discovered his sexuality.
The winner of two bronze medals at the Olympics has become a prominent figure in the LGBT movement and his image has been used in the Commonwealth Games held in Australia this year to call for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he told his story because he felt fortunate to live in freedom, without reprisals, and wanted to transmit that "hope" to other people.
The three-time world champion declared that it was also a surprise for her to fall in love with a man, the American film director Dustin Lance Black, whom she met in 2013.
Daley married last year the winner of an Oscar, who is 20 years older than her, although she specified that the age difference had never been a problem.
“When you live so much from such a young age (she was at her first Olympics at 14 and her father died of cancer three years later), it’s hard to find someone of the same age who has gone through the same highs and lows that you have.”
The couple had a son in June, whom they named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said that his "global perspective" had changed.
"If they had asked me a year ago, all my answers would have been about 'I have to win a gold medal'," she said.
But you know what, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My gold medal from the Olympics is, without a doubt, Robbie's.
His son is named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with a brain cancer.
Daley said that his father did not accept that he was going to die and, in fact, one of the last things he asked is if they had the tickets for the London 2012 Olympics, because he wanted to be in the first row.
She said, "I couldn't tell him I couldn't be in the first row."
“I had his hand in mine when he stopped breathing and it wasn’t until that precise moment when he stopped breathing and died that I realized he wasn’t invincible,” she said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
"In that moment I knew that was what I had dreamed of all my life: competing in the pool in front of my family at the Olympics, there was nothing better," she said.
This fact was also the one that inspired him to choose his first song, Proud, by Heather Small, which accompanied him during the preparation for the Olympic Games. He still got goosebumps.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on the BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
