The new German warship has been postponed again.
The new frigate of the German Navy was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old frigates of the Cold War era, but it will not be commissioned until at least next year due to defective systems and the progressive increase in costs, according to local media.
The delivery of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the ship that leads the new class of Baden-Württemberg frigates, has been postponed now until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery delayed the completion of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class frigates requested by the German Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
We know that they will include a powerful cannon, a set of air-to-air missiles and anti-missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as radar signals, infrared and acoustic signatures, which are very reduced.
Some of the most important features include longer maintenance periods, so that they can be deployed for up to two years away from their home ports.
However, the constant delays have meant that the innovative warships (which were supposed to allow Germany to project its power into the oceans) will already be out of date when they go into service, as Die Zeit points out.
The unfortunate frigate F125 was in the news last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It has been the first time that the Navy has returned a ship to a shipyard after delivery.
Very little was known about the reasons behind the return, but German media cited a number of "software and hardware defects" that left the ship practically useless if it was sent on a combat mission.
Deficiencies in software were particularly important, since the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors: half the crew that had been on the old frigates of the class Bremen.
In addition, it was found that the ship has an excessive weight, which reduces its performance and limits the capacity of the Navy to add future updates.
It is believed that the "Rheinland-Pfalz" of 7,000 tons is twice as heavy as other ships of the same class that the Germans used in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project, including the training of the crew, has also been a problem.
It is believed to have reached 3.1 billion € (3.6 billion $), instead of the initial 2.2 billion €.
The problems that are being attributed to the new frigates are of special relevance in light of the recent warnings about the reduction in the power of the German navy.
At the beginning of this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defense committee of the German parliament, admitted that the Navy is "running out of ships that can be deployed."
The official said that the problem has been getting worse over time, because the old ships have been decommissioned, but they have not been replaced with new ones.
He lamented that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret life of the bats
This new research, which has been carried out in the Highlands of Scotland, is trying to find out how bats use the landscape to find food.
It is hoped that what is discovered will shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help to guide the next conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano pipistrelle bats, as well as Daubenton's bats and brown long-eared bats in the gardens of Inverewe in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in strategic locations on the property to monitor the activities of the bats during the season.
The template and volunteers from the NHS will also carry out mobile investigations with portable detectors.
The experts will analyze the sounds recorded in the recordings to discover the frequency of the calls of the bats and what species make them.
Then a report and a map of the habitat will be produced to create a detailed image of the environment and of its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation advisor for NTS, is hoping that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how each species uses them.
With this information, it will be possible to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how they should be maintained for bats and other species associated with them.
The populations of bats in Scotland and in the United Kingdom have decreased considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
The wind turbines and the electrical cabling can also pose a risk to them, as well as insecticides and other chemical treatments of the construction materials or attacks by domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful to them than their eyes in finding their prey.
They use a sophisticated technique of ecolocalization that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The National Trust, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in the matter, who carry out regular surveys, inspections of nests and, in some cases, rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated the first and only reserve dedicated to bats in Scotland in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is the home of eight of the ten species of bat in Scotland.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says that it is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, at Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many old trees, and all the right habitat.
However, there are still many things unknown about bats, so the work that we do here and at other properties will help us to understand better what they need to develop.
He points out the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance work inside properties, as it is possible to accidentally destroy a colony of breeding bats and kill up to 400 females and their young, which would mean wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, or destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how they evolve their populations."
