Brexit: the United Kingdom would regret losing car manufacturers forever
The United Kingdom would "regret it for the rest of its life" if it lost its position as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit, said the Secretary of State for Business, Greg Clark.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that, if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at its factory in Burnaston, near Derby.
Mr. Clark said, "We need an agreement."
The Japanese manufacturer stated that the impact of delays at the border in the case of a Brexit without a deal could result in the loss of jobs.
The Burnaston plant, which makes Auris and Avensis models for Toyota, produced 150 000 cars last year, of which 90 % were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"My opinion is that, if Britain breaks with the EU at the end of March, there will be parones of production in our factory," said Marvin Cooke, the general director of Toyota in Burnaston.
Other car manufacturers from the United Kingdom have shown their fears in relation to the exit of the EU without an agreement, especially in relation to cross-border trade; among them, Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
For example, BMW says that it will close its Mini plant in Oxford a month after the Brexit.
The main concerns that the car manufacturers are referring to are the problems that could arise in the factories in the case of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is based on the "just in time" method, where parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers in the UK and the EU to make cars by order.
If the UK leaves the EU on March 29 without an agreement, there could be a disruption at the border, which, according to the sector, could cause delays and a shortage of parts.
For Toyota, it would be impossible to house the amount of material equivalent to more than a day's worth of inventory in its Derbyshire plant, the company said and, in such a case, production would be halted.
Mr. Clark said that the Chequers plan of Theresa May, where the future relations with the EU are established, is "precisely calibrated to avoid those controls at the border".
