Foreigners will have to pay a higher rate of stamp duty when they buy a property in the UK.
A foreigners will have to pay a higher stamp duty when they buy a property in the UK and the extra money will be used to give shelter to the homeless.
The change will neutralize the success of Corbyn's offensive to attract younger voters.
The increase in the transmission of land tax will be applied to those people who are not paying taxes in the United Kingdom.
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year which will be used to help the homeless.
The additional money raised by the increase in stamp duty for foreign buyers of property in the UK will be used to help the homeless, announced Theresa May today.
The measure is understood as an attempt to neutralize the success that Jeremy Corbyn is having with his promises to provide more affordable housing to attract younger voters and to ease the burden on those with higher incomes.
The increase in stamp duty on property will be levied on people and companies who do not pay taxes in the UK and that money will be used to incentivise the government's policy to combat begging on the streets.
The surcharge, which is a supplement to the current transmission tax, also includes the increase in levels that was introduced two years ago on second-hand homes and the "buy-to-let" system, which could reach up to 3 %.
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year with this change.
It is estimated that 13% of new properties in London are bought by people who do not live in the UK, which causes prices to rise and makes it difficult for first-time buyers to get on the property ladder.
Many of the more affluent areas of the country (especially in the capital) have become "ghost cities" due to the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just a few weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in stamp duty in order to help young people buy their first home.
He accused the big builders of keeping the prices very high for the properties by buying land without any intention of using it and asked the Sra. May to get rid of the fees that are applied to affordable homes to solve the "shameful problem of housing" in Britain.
Mr. Corbyn has announced a series of very attractive reforms for housing, among which are controls on rent and the end of evictions without cause.
He also proposes to give local authorities more powers to build new homes.
The Prime Minister's wife, Mrs. May, said: "Last year I said I would dedicate my time as Prime Minister to restoring the British dream of improving the life chances of every new generation."
And that means solving the housing market, which is so badly damaged.
Britain will always be open to those who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it cannot be that people who do not live in the United Kingdom, as well as foreign companies, can buy homes more easily than the working class in Britain.
The dream of having a home has become too difficult to achieve for many people and the humiliation of having to sleep on the street is still too real.
