The numbers of deserters from North Korea "fall" with Kim
The number of deserters from North Korea to South Korea has decreased since Kim Jong-un came to power seven years ago, a South Korean lawmaker said.
Park Byeong-seug, citing data from the Ministry of Unification of the South, said that there were 1,127 desertions last year, compared with 2,706 in 2011.
Park said that the stricter border controls between North Korea and China, and the high fees charged by human traffickers, have been the key factors.
Pyongyang has not made any public comments on the matter.
The vast majority of deserters from the North are eventually offered citizenship in South Korea.
Seoul says that more than 30,000 North Koreans have crossed illegally into South Korea since the end of the Korean War in 1953.
The majority flee through China, which has the longest border with North Korea and which is easier to cross than the heavily protected demilitarized zone (DMZ) between the two Koreas.
China considers deserters to be illegal immigrants instead of refugees, and they are often repatriated.
Relations between the North and the South, which are still technically at war, have improved significantly in the last few months.
At the beginning of the month, the leaders of the two countries met in Pyongyang to have conversations that focused on the negotiations of nuclear disarmament.
This happened after the historic meeting in June between US President Donald Trump and North Korean leader Kim Jong-un in Singapore, where they agreed in general terms to work towards a nuclear-free Korean Peninsula.
But on Saturday, the foreign minister of North Korea, Ri Yong-ho, blamed the lack of progress on U.S. sanctions.
“Without the confidence of the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and, under these circumstances, we will not be the first to disarm unilaterally,” Ri said in a speech before the United Nations General Assembly in New York.
