The trade war between the U.S. and China could benefit Beijing.
The first salvos of the trade war between the U.S. and China were deafening, and although the battle is far from over, a rupture between the two countries could benefit Beijing, according to experts.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, issued the first warning at the beginning of the year by imposing tariffs on the main Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs that affect 200 billion dollars (150 billion pounds sterling) in products, which will add taxes to half of the products that enter the United States from China.
In all cases, Beijing has taken retaliatory measures, applying tariffs of five to ten percent on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has committed to equalizing the attacks of the U.S., and it is unlikely that the second most powerful economy in the world is going to back down soon.
It would be too humiliating for Chinese President Xi Jinping to submit to the United States.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, the trade war with the United States could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic crash in either of the two countries is actually much more dangerous than what the spectators have recognized so far, said Abigail Grace, a research associate focused on Asia at the Center for New American Security.
Syria is ready for the return of refugees, says the Minister of Foreign Affairs
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been going on for more than seven years.
In a speech before the General Assembly of the United Nations, the Minister of Foreign Affairs Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions in the country were improving.
“The situation on the ground is today more stable and safer thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is still trying to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by the terrorists in order to try to restore normality.
All the conditions are in place for the voluntary return of the refugees who had to leave their country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and their means of living.
The U.N. estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled their country since the war began in 2011.
There are still six million people who live in the country and who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would be grateful for the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional help or the help of the countries that promoted the insurgency.
