Update of the red tide: Decrease in concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission) shows a general reduction in the concentrations of red tide in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in parts of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which suggests a reduction in concentrations.
The bloom of the red tide extends approximately 130 miles along the Florida coast from Pinellas County to Lee County.
Irregular parcels can be found as far as 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in the county of Pasco.
During the past week, concentrations have been notified in the County of Pinellas and on its coast, concentrations between low and high in the County of Hillsborough, concentrations of low to high in the County of Manatee, concentrations of low to high in the County of Sarasota and its coast, concentrations of low to high in the County of Charlotte, concentrations of low to high in the County of Lee and on its coast, and concentrations of low to high in the County of Collier.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to come in from the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwestern part of Florida during the past week.
